16
00:00:46,942 --> 00:00:49,624
is, it's making games great, making great player

17
00:00:49,664 --> 00:00:50,145
experiences.

18
00:00:50,805 --> 00:00:53,367
But these problems that these are trying to solve, a lot of

19
00:00:53,407 --> 00:00:56,450
them feel more like, they feel kind of like pearl diving.

20
00:00:57,070 --> 00:00:58,952
Like there are all these solutions out there, and you

21
00:00:58,972 --> 00:01:00,293
have this huge array of them to pick from.

22
00:01:00,313 --> 00:01:02,675
And what you're looking for is the best, shiniest pearl to

23
00:01:02,715 --> 00:01:04,176
make your game as perfect as it can be.

24
00:01:05,017 --> 00:01:06,178
And that's great, and it's really important.

25
00:01:06,880 --> 00:01:10,405
But I've often found myself more drawn to a different kind of design problem.

26
00:01:11,227 --> 00:01:12,789
One that's more like wandering the desert.

27
00:01:14,091 --> 00:01:17,437
For days, months, maybe even years, looking for a solution,

28
00:01:17,917 --> 00:01:21,162
wondering where one might be, and thinking maybe one doesn't even exist.

29
00:01:22,489 --> 00:01:27,430
So, the thing that's gotten me so maybe interested in these incredibly hard design problems is

30
00:01:27,890 --> 00:01:28,470
my own background.

31
00:01:28,490 --> 00:01:29,251
I'm Alex.

32
00:01:29,591 --> 00:01:30,571
Hi.

33
00:01:31,031 --> 00:01:33,191
I used to be a mathematician for a few years.

34
00:01:34,312 --> 00:01:38,672
And when I was a mathematician, you know, I would spend so long on like one problem.

35
00:01:38,873 --> 00:01:40,793
One problem that maybe people have worked on for decades.

36
00:01:40,813 --> 00:01:42,193
And you'd usually make no progress.

37
00:01:42,393 --> 00:01:45,614
You'd spend, again, months or years on it, just kind of banging your head against it.

38
00:01:46,034 --> 00:01:48,855
And eventually you build a sort of Stockholm syndrome with a problem.

39
00:01:49,215 --> 00:01:51,175
Like, you come to love the way this thing tortures you,

40
00:01:51,415 --> 00:01:53,476
and you think, maybe I can learn more from this problem

41
00:01:53,496 --> 00:01:54,616
than I even can from the solution.

42
00:01:55,456 --> 00:01:56,977
And I think there's really some truth to that, right?

43
00:01:56,997 --> 00:01:59,457
Problems realign our thinking when they're really well-posed.

44
00:01:59,777 --> 00:02:01,878
Sometimes finding the solution isn't the most important part.

45
00:02:02,438 --> 00:02:03,718
And so that's what's inspired this talk,

46
00:02:03,738 --> 00:02:05,859
and for years I've kind of wanted to focus on this topic.

47
00:02:06,199 --> 00:02:08,299
And I've thought about it as I did my PhD

48
00:02:08,499 --> 00:02:10,360
in essentially computational game balancing

49
00:02:10,600 --> 00:02:11,480
at the University of Washington.

50
00:02:12,469 --> 00:02:16,891
And I've been a designer at Superbot, Congregate, and Spryfox, as well as a data scientist.

51
00:02:17,592 --> 00:02:21,894
And now I'm a designer at Riot Games and R&D in the Bay Area office.

52
00:02:21,914 --> 00:02:22,835
It's pretty awesome.

53
00:02:22,855 --> 00:02:25,216
A lot of you may not even know it exists, but it's a great place.

54
00:02:26,577 --> 00:02:29,699
And so all this time I've been thinking about hard design problems.

55
00:02:31,060 --> 00:02:34,702
And what I've wondered is, all these different problems that if you pay attention to game

56
00:02:34,722 --> 00:02:35,623
design you start to notice.

57
00:02:36,530 --> 00:02:40,292
I'm wondering if there's anything kind of shared, any shared DNA between them that causes

58
00:02:40,312 --> 00:02:43,794
them to be so hard, that causes them to maybe even be impossible.

59
00:02:45,575 --> 00:02:50,478
And yeah, I think I know what that is, at least for many of them, and that, you may

60
00:02:50,518 --> 00:02:52,258
not be surprised, is that they are cursed.

61
00:02:54,520 --> 00:02:57,741
I'll get to a definition in a minute, what this means, and I'll also get you some examples

62
00:02:57,761 --> 00:03:01,163
because I know you want to know what at least one hard problem is, but first an outline.

63
00:03:02,384 --> 00:03:02,484
So.

64
00:03:03,243 --> 00:03:04,464
There are basically two parts to this talk.

65
00:03:04,944 --> 00:03:09,347
In the first part, I tell you what curse problems are and where to find them.

66
00:03:10,508 --> 00:03:13,750
And basically, this is important because, look, the problems I'm going to talk about

67
00:03:13,770 --> 00:03:18,693
today, the category of problems, they really don't have a clear solution.

68
00:03:18,733 --> 00:03:19,993
You can't just go in and solve them.

69
00:03:20,334 --> 00:03:22,815
You really have to know that they are right in your face

70
00:03:22,835 --> 00:03:26,097
so that you don't waste your time and your team's energy on them.

71
00:03:26,678 --> 00:03:28,178
And so this is the most important part of the talk.

72
00:03:28,219 --> 00:03:30,160
The talk where we understand what curse problems are

73
00:03:30,420 --> 00:03:31,320
and can actually identify them.

74
00:03:31,501 --> 00:03:32,641
And that's what I do. I define them.

75
00:03:33,242 --> 00:03:34,002
I show you an example.

76
00:03:34,683 --> 00:03:38,545
And then I sort of give you maybe some intuition for how to identify them

77
00:03:38,605 --> 00:03:39,866
through the use of a bunch of examples.

78
00:03:40,226 --> 00:03:41,667
Okay? So that's the first part.

79
00:03:42,822 --> 00:03:45,283
But the second part is defense against curse problems.

80
00:03:45,803 --> 00:03:47,724
It's what to do when you come up against a curse problem,

81
00:03:47,944 --> 00:03:51,046
and you have no choice but to bear right ahead.

82
00:03:51,366 --> 00:03:52,907
Or hopefully, what I'm really going to tell you you have to

83
00:03:52,947 --> 00:03:55,468
do is you have to tilt a little to the side, because

84
00:03:55,568 --> 00:03:56,508
you can't solve the problem.

85
00:03:56,809 --> 00:03:58,970
But maybe you can give up some part of what you're trying to

86
00:03:59,010 --> 00:04:00,170
do, and you can solve that.

87
00:04:00,791 --> 00:04:03,332
And so what I'll do is I'll tell you a model for how I

88
00:04:03,352 --> 00:04:04,693
think about games in this context.

89
00:04:05,433 --> 00:04:07,294
And then I'll talk about four techniques

90
00:04:07,934 --> 00:04:09,455
for addressing curse problems.

91
00:04:09,875 --> 00:04:11,196
Remember, I said I'm not going to solve them

92
00:04:11,496 --> 00:04:12,637
because they are unsolvable,

93
00:04:12,917 --> 00:04:14,277
but there will be ways to handle them.

94
00:04:14,698 --> 00:04:16,078
And these are techniques that I've sort of...

95
00:04:16,538 --> 00:04:18,279
I've taken a look at all the techniques

96
00:04:18,479 --> 00:04:20,000
game developers have used over decades

97
00:04:20,380 --> 00:04:21,441
to address problems like these

98
00:04:21,501 --> 00:04:23,462
and kind of bucketed them into these four categories.

99
00:04:23,802 --> 00:04:24,823
And I think it's a helpful framing

100
00:04:24,843 --> 00:04:26,463
for what to do when you encounter one.

101
00:04:27,484 --> 00:04:29,585
And finally, I'll show some more applications of these techniques

102
00:04:29,925 --> 00:04:31,466
so you build intuition for how to apply them

103
00:04:31,506 --> 00:04:32,106
if you ever get there.

104
00:04:32,126 --> 00:04:33,667
All right, everyone on board?

105
00:04:34,668 --> 00:04:34,868
Here we go.

106
00:04:36,188 --> 00:04:36,828
Let's have a definition.

107
00:04:37,929 --> 00:04:39,851
This is actually a sub-definition I need, real quick.

108
00:04:40,912 --> 00:04:42,473
Player promises, you may have heard of them.

109
00:04:43,013 --> 00:04:45,435
I consider them a game's essential experiences.

110
00:04:45,976 --> 00:04:47,857
Why did the player actually come to play this, right?

111
00:04:47,877 --> 00:04:48,938
What is the core of this game?

112
00:04:50,459 --> 00:04:52,201
Zach McClendon has a talk, Welcome to the Yard Sale,

113
00:04:52,221 --> 00:04:53,642
which talks a lot about player promises,

114
00:04:53,762 --> 00:04:55,443
if you want to learn more about them, it's a great talk.

115
00:04:56,532 --> 00:04:58,856
But for me, the key thing that's happening here is that

116
00:04:59,297 --> 00:05:00,800
promises live in the designer's heart.

117
00:05:01,481 --> 00:05:03,885
It's the thing that is driving us to make this game.

118
00:05:04,346 --> 00:05:06,129
It's what we care about at the fundamental level, the stuff

119
00:05:06,149 --> 00:05:06,811
we don't want to give up.

120
00:05:08,105 --> 00:05:10,687
But often, weirdly, they also can lie in the player's heart.

121
00:05:11,627 --> 00:05:13,928
Sometimes you give a player something really simple,

122
00:05:13,968 --> 00:05:15,769
just a few mechanics, a few systems,

123
00:05:16,089 --> 00:05:17,650
and then they immediately come to believe

124
00:05:17,670 --> 00:05:20,091
that the game owes them something specific.

125
00:05:20,791 --> 00:05:22,732
And you kind of have to accept that.

126
00:05:22,752 --> 00:05:25,133
You have to deal with the fact that you've made this promise

127
00:05:25,153 --> 00:05:27,454
to a player whether you meant to or not,

128
00:05:28,015 --> 00:05:29,115
and you have to adapt.

129
00:05:30,276 --> 00:05:31,916
So, now that we've outlined what promises are,

130
00:05:32,417 --> 00:05:33,297
the curse problem definition.

131
00:05:34,200 --> 00:05:38,444
It is an unsolvable design problem rooted in a conflict between core player promises.

132
00:05:38,464 --> 00:05:40,285
You're going to see this slide a lot.

133
00:05:41,046 --> 00:05:44,569
So it's basically any time I'm trying to solve a design problem and I have implicitly or

134
00:05:44,629 --> 00:05:48,933
explicitly promised two things that cannot coexist, it is surprisingly common.

135
00:05:50,234 --> 00:05:53,337
So one of the properties here is there is no direct solution.

136
00:05:53,397 --> 00:05:55,539
One does not simply solve curse problems.

137
00:05:56,620 --> 00:05:59,281
You have to instead, you have to work around it.

138
00:05:59,722 --> 00:06:01,362
You have to give something up.

139
00:06:01,402 --> 00:06:02,983
Like the Gordian Knot, you kind of have to cut through

140
00:06:03,003 --> 00:06:06,965
the problem itself and find a kind of a strange non-solution.

141
00:06:08,946 --> 00:06:10,046
So, that's the definition.

142
00:06:10,066 --> 00:06:11,107
And now you finally get an example.

143
00:06:11,147 --> 00:06:11,847
Thank you for your patience.

144
00:06:12,307 --> 00:06:14,908
The example will be a little hypothetical at first,

145
00:06:15,188 --> 00:06:17,089
but it will become more concrete as I move through it.

146
00:06:18,270 --> 00:06:19,950
So I'll talk about Free For All Politics,

147
00:06:19,990 --> 00:06:21,491
which I consider a cursed classic.

148
00:06:23,592 --> 00:06:25,413
So a cursed problem often begins with a dream.

149
00:06:26,610 --> 00:06:29,392
Say it's the 90s, and you love beat-em-ups.

150
00:06:29,892 --> 00:06:31,373
You love the punchin' and the kickin'

151
00:06:31,793 --> 00:06:34,394
and like a crowd control, lots of enemies to defeat.

152
00:06:35,214 --> 00:06:37,555
And it's also the 90s, and so at some point,

153
00:06:37,575 --> 00:06:39,176
Street Fighter II comes out, and you're like,

154
00:06:39,236 --> 00:06:40,077
wow, this is amazing.

155
00:06:40,097 --> 00:06:42,198
I get all this really high-skill execution,

156
00:06:42,238 --> 00:06:44,379
all this tactical choice-making, knowledge tests.

157
00:06:44,419 --> 00:06:47,080
I get to read my opponent's mind and act accordingly.

158
00:06:47,140 --> 00:06:49,301
And you think, maybe these are two great tastes

159
00:06:49,321 --> 00:06:50,181
that would go great together.

160
00:06:51,123 --> 00:06:54,245
How about we give a controller to every one of these characters and we make this huge

161
00:06:54,785 --> 00:06:59,487
martial arts brawler game, everybody fighting it out with the technical execution and the

162
00:06:59,527 --> 00:07:05,170
tactics of a fighting game, but the kind of crowd control and chaos of a beat-em-up.

163
00:07:06,251 --> 00:07:10,293
This seems like I think a perfectly reasonable hypothetical game, something that would sound

164
00:07:10,333 --> 00:07:10,833
exciting to me.

165
00:07:10,873 --> 00:07:12,194
I think it's a nice fantasy.

166
00:07:13,474 --> 00:07:17,556
But as you go to make this, you want this really, really high competitive integrity

167
00:07:17,596 --> 00:07:19,097
game that's all about managing your opponents.

168
00:07:20,104 --> 00:07:23,726
You notice something weird, which is the best player,

169
00:07:23,786 --> 00:07:25,948
say, Gene's dude with the jump,

170
00:07:27,249 --> 00:07:28,589
that player, the one who's great at tactics

171
00:07:28,629 --> 00:07:31,211
and great at buttons and great at mind reading,

172
00:07:31,531 --> 00:07:32,332
isn't actually winning.

173
00:07:33,152 --> 00:07:33,893
Other players are winning.

174
00:07:34,833 --> 00:07:36,154
And the reason why is politics,

175
00:07:36,875 --> 00:07:38,315
which I'll define as competition

176
00:07:38,335 --> 00:07:41,878
through social negotiation, alliances, and manipulation.

177
00:07:42,818 --> 00:07:46,960
And there's some great treatment of politics in Characteristics of Games by Elias Garfield

178
00:07:47,060 --> 00:07:47,640
and Gushera.

179
00:07:48,141 --> 00:07:51,782
This is probably my favorite, or at least one of my favorite game design textbooks and

180
00:07:51,802 --> 00:07:54,144
it is sorely under read, so please check it out.

181
00:07:58,829 --> 00:08:03,071
What happens is players start to play this game, they sit down to play, and you realize

182
00:08:03,111 --> 00:08:07,054
that they immediately figure out who the best player is in terms of the core gameplay.

183
00:08:07,394 --> 00:08:10,676
And instead they start forming alliances against this player, they gang up on them.

184
00:08:11,376 --> 00:08:13,437
They maybe pretend to be their friend and betray this person.

185
00:08:14,978 --> 00:08:18,560
They play down and pretend not to be too strong and then at the last minute they strike and

186
00:08:19,120 --> 00:08:19,681
kick ass.

187
00:08:19,921 --> 00:08:23,183
And what happens is you realize that the core skill of playing this game is not the skill

188
00:08:23,203 --> 00:08:24,043
that you were emphasizing.

189
00:08:24,664 --> 00:08:25,704
It's not the game you thought you were making.

190
00:08:25,724 --> 00:08:27,666
This is a game of Thrones.

191
00:08:28,046 --> 00:08:31,829
This is a game entirely about politics and manipulation.

192
00:08:32,210 --> 00:08:34,712
And maybe punching well is helpful,

193
00:08:34,752 --> 00:08:37,274
but it's not really what you cared about as a designer,

194
00:08:37,314 --> 00:08:38,675
and probably not what the player expected.

195
00:08:39,996 --> 00:08:43,018
So, remember, a curse problem is an unsolvable design problem

196
00:08:43,359 --> 00:08:45,681
rooted in a conflict between core player promises.

197
00:08:46,521 --> 00:08:47,082
So in this case...

198
00:08:48,178 --> 00:08:52,102
A player looks at this game, they look at all the, you know, the difficult execution,

199
00:08:52,462 --> 00:08:54,764
they look at, you know, all the moves you can do, and they think this is a game about

200
00:08:54,864 --> 00:08:55,705
combat mastery.

201
00:08:56,446 --> 00:09:00,129
I want to focus on combat mastery and be great at this, and I want the game to, you know,

202
00:09:00,169 --> 00:09:01,010
emphasize that correctly.

203
00:09:01,551 --> 00:09:04,394
But it's also, it's a, you know, we've made this really competitive game, it emphasizes

204
00:09:04,414 --> 00:09:05,675
the winner, I want to play to win.

205
00:09:06,856 --> 00:09:09,759
These are both reasonable promises to take away from the game I've described.

206
00:09:10,519 --> 00:09:12,201
But these promises are incompatible.

207
00:09:12,910 --> 00:09:16,513
Because playing to win in a free-for-all game requires politics.

208
00:09:16,573 --> 00:09:18,594
It is the optimal strategy from a game theoretic standpoint,

209
00:09:18,634 --> 00:09:19,875
from a psychological standpoint.

210
00:09:20,496 --> 00:09:23,598
But the focus on combat mastery is not compatible with political play.

211
00:09:23,638 --> 00:09:25,379
They're different player emphases.

212
00:09:25,920 --> 00:09:27,441
And so you end up with this big nope.

213
00:09:27,501 --> 00:09:28,942
You can't make this game.

214
00:09:28,982 --> 00:09:29,942
The game is cursed.

215
00:09:30,443 --> 00:09:30,643
All right?

216
00:09:30,803 --> 00:09:32,564
This game you have in your head is cursed.

217
00:09:34,125 --> 00:09:34,346
So.

218
00:09:35,357 --> 00:09:37,098
You're probably wondering, well, can't I do something?

219
00:09:37,138 --> 00:09:38,558
And yes, you can do something.

220
00:09:38,598 --> 00:09:39,759
You can get out of the situation.

221
00:09:40,379 --> 00:09:43,140
But it requires giving something up.

222
00:09:43,200 --> 00:09:45,941
It requires changing something about your core premise.

223
00:09:46,801 --> 00:09:48,201
So it's a fantasy.

224
00:09:48,641 --> 00:09:49,042
What do you do?

225
00:09:49,742 --> 00:09:51,542
You let go of the dream, at least a little bit.

226
00:09:53,243 --> 00:09:55,263
So one thing you could do, just an example, is you could

227
00:09:55,304 --> 00:09:56,484
weaken the promises.

228
00:09:57,304 --> 00:09:59,965
So we said the promises were to focus on combat mastery and

229
00:10:00,005 --> 00:10:00,725
also to play to win.

230
00:10:01,463 --> 00:10:03,563
But maybe we change our game a little bit to weaken these.

231
00:10:03,603 --> 00:10:06,764
We pour in a little bit of chaos, and we end up with a

232
00:10:06,784 --> 00:10:08,965
game where you kind of want a chance to do some cool moves

233
00:10:09,005 --> 00:10:10,485
if you can, but you don't really expect it.

234
00:10:11,406 --> 00:10:14,627
And you want to win if possible, but it doesn't feel

235
00:10:14,647 --> 00:10:16,787
like something you can really, really guarantee just by being

236
00:10:17,227 --> 00:10:18,288
the best at the core skills.

237
00:10:19,330 --> 00:10:22,494
And when you do this, you make these changes, you change,

238
00:10:23,054 --> 00:10:26,258
weaken the promises here, you end up with something that might even be better,

239
00:10:26,318 --> 00:10:27,739
even though it's not what you initially expected.

240
00:10:28,300 --> 00:10:29,581
You end up with Smash Brothers.

241
00:10:30,002 --> 00:10:31,403
This is a very good beloved game.

242
00:10:32,624 --> 00:10:34,446
It basically takes this premise I described and says,

243
00:10:34,526 --> 00:10:36,268
screw it, just like let it be crazy.

244
00:10:36,308 --> 00:10:39,672
I'm not talking about the 1v1 game without the items on, you know, Final Destination.

245
00:10:39,972 --> 00:10:41,193
I'm talking about, like, the party game.

246
00:10:41,754 --> 00:10:47,519
