I might not pay attention to my friends.

492
00:21:40,897 --> 00:21:42,458
So what I'm wondering, these two things,

493
00:21:43,558 --> 00:21:46,199
the game kind of demands rewards at specific times and places

494
00:21:46,219 --> 00:21:48,179
to make it feel like it has that magical overlay,

495
00:21:48,719 --> 00:21:51,920
but also there's this need for personal safety and convenience

496
00:21:52,020 --> 00:21:53,920
and also mindfulness at some level

497
00:21:54,320 --> 00:21:56,701
that I think is a basic need that the game doesn't promise,

498
00:21:56,721 --> 00:21:58,221
but we assume games will not violate.

499
00:21:58,781 --> 00:22:00,202
So, who thinks it's cursed?

500
00:22:02,322 --> 00:22:03,823
All right. Who thinks it's just really hard?

501
00:22:04,877 --> 00:22:07,918
Alright, I want to know how you guys want to solve this, because

502
00:22:09,779 --> 00:22:13,260
because for the life of me, these two things seem fundamentally incompatible.

503
00:22:14,760 --> 00:22:19,302
So, I think the... Now, I know why this might happen, why it might seem hard.

504
00:22:19,322 --> 00:22:24,303
So I'm saying that this is cursed, because you sort of need to be able to play anywhere at any time

505
00:22:25,163 --> 00:22:29,125
in order to satisfy the first promise, but to satisfy the second, you need to play when appropriate.

506
00:22:29,960 --> 00:22:32,702
And I know why it might seem like this is just a hard problem,

507
00:22:32,722 --> 00:22:35,364
because you're like, well surely we can put limits in the game, right?

508
00:22:35,404 --> 00:22:38,026
We can make it so you only see, you know,

509
00:22:39,006 --> 00:22:40,728
monsters at times that are appropriate,

510
00:22:40,748 --> 00:22:42,409
or when other people are playing around you, or something like that.

511
00:22:42,869 --> 00:22:43,970
And I think that all of those,

512
00:22:44,530 --> 00:22:45,771
once we get a little further into Chris' problems,

513
00:22:45,791 --> 00:22:49,434
we see that all of those kind of are violating that first promise to some extent.

514
00:22:50,450 --> 00:22:54,293
And so that's why I say this is cursed, because the moves that you have to make to actually

515
00:22:54,954 --> 00:23:00,358
make the situation go away kind of turn it into a different game, at least a little bit.

516
00:23:00,378 --> 00:23:04,761
And I think that's why you still have these problems in these games years later, right?

517
00:23:04,801 --> 00:23:06,983
Because you don't want to break that first core promise.

518
00:23:08,064 --> 00:23:08,204
Okay.

519
00:23:09,405 --> 00:23:13,248
So, generally, I'd call this like the life disruption problem, and there are other very

520
00:23:13,308 --> 00:23:15,290
different games that encounter these problems.

521
00:23:16,556 --> 00:23:17,236
So this is where we are.

522
00:23:18,417 --> 00:23:20,098
The big ocean there is your game.

523
00:23:20,138 --> 00:23:21,879
It's a wide sea of possibilities,

524
00:23:22,280 --> 00:23:24,201
all kinds of things for players to do, have fun.

525
00:23:24,681 --> 00:23:27,623
And that eldritch horror living in the heart of your game

526
00:23:27,683 --> 00:23:28,924
is your curse problem.

527
00:23:28,944 --> 00:23:30,545
They're just there underneath the sea,

528
00:23:30,965 --> 00:23:32,386
kind of corrupting everything around them.

529
00:23:32,806 --> 00:23:33,547
And it's not like a fish,

530
00:23:33,567 --> 00:23:34,888
you can't just like spear it and pull it out.

531
00:23:35,268 --> 00:23:37,590
The thing about Cthulhu is he's not leaving the ocean,

532
00:23:37,630 --> 00:23:38,450
like he's just there.

533
00:23:38,470 --> 00:23:41,772
It's core baked into the premise of your game.

534
00:23:42,513 --> 00:23:43,934
So what do you do when you encounter

535
00:23:43,974 --> 00:23:45,855
an eldritch horror that won't leave?

536
00:23:46,765 --> 00:23:48,627
You make sacrifices. You kill your babies.

537
00:23:52,750 --> 00:23:54,391
And that's what we're going to do.

538
00:23:54,831 --> 00:23:57,493
There's four little kinds of sacrifices down here we can make.

539
00:23:58,214 --> 00:24:00,335
And each of them is a little different, right?

540
00:24:00,355 --> 00:24:02,777
They're different ways of giving up some subtle,

541
00:24:02,837 --> 00:24:06,420
sometimes implicit piece of one of your promises.

542
00:24:07,921 --> 00:24:08,741
And that's the rest of the talk.

543
00:24:09,255 --> 00:24:09,456
OK?

544
00:24:09,936 --> 00:24:11,737
So we've talked about curse problems.

545
00:24:11,757 --> 00:24:13,358
We've talked about why they are hard,

546
00:24:13,658 --> 00:24:15,880
why they will likely screw you over if you don't notice them.

547
00:24:16,280 --> 00:24:17,221
Now we're going to say, all right, well,

548
00:24:17,261 --> 00:24:18,362
if you still are dealing with one,

549
00:24:18,422 --> 00:24:19,503
if you still want to make this game,

550
00:24:19,843 --> 00:24:22,004
how can you make a sacrifice, give up

551
00:24:22,024 --> 00:24:24,166
some piece of your fantasy, and make a slightly different game

552
00:24:24,186 --> 00:24:26,888
that hopefully still makes you happy, still is good enough?

553
00:24:27,988 --> 00:24:29,429
So first I'll present a game model.

554
00:24:29,990 --> 00:24:31,911
How I think about a game that will build

555
00:24:31,951 --> 00:24:32,912
these techniques on top of.

556
00:24:33,772 --> 00:24:35,854
And it will look scary at first, but it won't be scary.

557
00:24:37,117 --> 00:24:39,599
So remember, a curse problem is an unsolvable design problem

558
00:24:39,939 --> 00:24:42,540
rooted in a conflict between core player promises.

559
00:24:44,782 --> 00:24:46,563
And I'm gonna talk about a common special case of this

560
00:24:47,443 --> 00:24:49,665
in which these two promises aren't just anything.

561
00:24:49,785 --> 00:24:52,086
One is an experience and one is an objective.

562
00:24:53,207 --> 00:24:55,388
So by experiences, I mean moment-to-moment gameplay.

563
00:24:55,448 --> 00:24:57,009
What is this game like to play?

564
00:24:58,390 --> 00:25:00,631
But by objectives, I mean like the goals of the game,

565
00:25:00,651 --> 00:25:02,652
the driving forces, the things that I'm trying

566
00:25:02,672 --> 00:25:03,773
to get out of the game in the end.

567
00:25:04,777 --> 00:25:06,939
And so these objectives are kind of pulling us through,

568
00:25:07,760 --> 00:25:09,501
motivating us through different experiences,

569
00:25:09,801 --> 00:25:11,623
whether we think they're great or not.

570
00:25:12,804 --> 00:25:15,786
And I think it's okay to limit us to just...

571
00:25:16,877 --> 00:25:20,620
This definition of curse problems for now, because first of all it covers a lot of the

572
00:25:20,640 --> 00:25:24,924
cases, probably more than half, but second it's just a much simpler case to talk about.

573
00:25:24,944 --> 00:25:28,968
The techniques I'm going to talk about are easier to explain in this context.

574
00:25:29,549 --> 00:25:33,573
They do generalize to the general case that looks like this, any two player promises.

575
00:25:33,933 --> 00:25:34,834
But we're focusing on this.

576
00:25:39,454 --> 00:25:40,716
Remember the free-for-all politics problem?

577
00:25:42,319 --> 00:25:45,224
So in this case, we have the desire to focus on combat mastery.

578
00:25:45,645 --> 00:25:46,867
That is an experience.

579
00:25:47,489 --> 00:25:49,753
And the desire to play to win is an objective.

580
00:25:50,274 --> 00:25:51,997
That's the kind of contrast I'm talking about.

581
00:25:53,497 --> 00:25:54,157
So here's my model.

582
00:25:54,517 --> 00:25:54,998
It's a game.

583
00:25:55,418 --> 00:25:57,219
Start state is S, and the objective

584
00:25:57,239 --> 00:25:58,580
is wherever you're going, O.

585
00:25:59,341 --> 00:26:00,902
And the objective can be given by the game,

586
00:26:00,922 --> 00:26:03,504
but often it's at least partially supplied by the player.

587
00:26:03,944 --> 00:26:05,425
And all the nodes in between are the play space.

588
00:26:05,445 --> 00:26:06,746
It's all the things you can do in the game.

589
00:26:07,167 --> 00:26:08,648
Kind of like a state machine, but you

590
00:26:08,668 --> 00:26:10,949
should think of these nodes as including

591
00:26:10,969 --> 00:26:12,671
kind of the player's mental state, as well as

592
00:26:12,931 --> 00:26:13,891
the digital state of the game.

593
00:26:15,144 --> 00:26:17,145
And these objectives, they pull players through the game.

594
00:26:17,165 --> 00:26:19,727
As I said, they kind of guide you into certain places one

595
00:26:19,787 --> 00:26:20,227
after another.

596
00:26:20,707 --> 00:26:22,468
And they guide you through this sort of golden path, like

597
00:26:22,528 --> 00:26:23,769
this is the right way to play.

598
00:26:23,989 --> 00:26:26,170
And you might not want to play this way, but it's what

599
00:26:26,190 --> 00:26:26,691
you're going to do.

600
00:26:26,751 --> 00:26:29,252
And there might be multiple golden paths, but I'm going to

601
00:26:29,272 --> 00:26:30,253
use one as an example.

602
00:26:31,293 --> 00:26:32,914
So I've abstracted a little.

603
00:26:33,855 --> 00:26:34,995
This here is your game.

604
00:26:35,916 --> 00:26:37,837
And this is your game on Curse Problems.

605
00:26:38,832 --> 00:26:44,417
This is the situation we get into, where the fire represents promises not being met.

606
00:26:44,457 --> 00:26:49,040
The experiential promise that was given by the designer or just the player imagined themselves

607
00:26:49,401 --> 00:26:52,303
is just not being met, but the player is taking themselves through it because they want to

608
00:26:52,323 --> 00:26:53,103
get to that objective.

609
00:26:53,844 --> 00:27:00,669
So to make this concrete, in this case, the fiery hellscape is political play, the grassy

610
00:27:00,769 --> 00:27:05,233
lovely area is unrestrained combat that players were promised, and the objective is winning.

611
00:27:07,770 --> 00:27:11,051
So, you notice by the way that they might spend a little bit of time in unrestrained combat.

612
00:27:11,071 --> 00:27:13,312
You're not doing political play all the time, but there's enough of it

613
00:27:13,692 --> 00:27:15,372
that this probably isn't what the players signed up for.

614
00:27:17,773 --> 00:27:19,954
So what can we do? What out are our options?

615
00:27:20,914 --> 00:27:23,295
Well, that is where these four techniques will come into play.

616
00:27:25,520 --> 00:27:28,462
Games have faced curse problems throughout time.

617
00:27:28,822 --> 00:27:31,503
Often, of course, people didn't know that they were facing them.

618
00:27:31,923 --> 00:27:33,984
Sometimes they didn't even know they were facing a hard problem at all

619
00:27:34,025 --> 00:27:38,267
because they naturally found their way into a way to address some previous hard problem.

620
00:27:38,947 --> 00:27:43,870
But along the way, nonetheless, designers have made sacrifices needed to address these problems.

621
00:27:44,390 --> 00:27:48,732
And really, I think these sacrifices really bucket nicely into four techniques.

622
00:27:50,660 --> 00:27:51,781
You don't really have to worry about it too much here.

623
00:27:51,801 --> 00:27:52,621
This is what they'll look like.

624
00:27:52,641 --> 00:27:53,762
This looks absurd.

625
00:27:54,022 --> 00:27:54,863
I know, it sounds absurd.

626
00:27:54,923 --> 00:27:57,024
Barriers, gates, carrots, and s'mores.

627
00:27:57,125 --> 00:27:58,486
Those are the four techniques I'll talk about.

628
00:27:58,506 --> 00:28:00,547
I'm going to go through them one by one so that they make sense.

629
00:28:02,368 --> 00:28:02,569
All right.

630
00:28:03,109 --> 00:28:04,430
So the first technique is barriers.

631
00:28:04,990 --> 00:28:08,493
This is cutting affordances that allow players to break promises.

632
00:28:08,533 --> 00:28:11,355
Basically, if a player is doing something that we don't want them to do,

633
00:28:11,755 --> 00:28:13,777
just make it impossible, if you can.

634
00:28:14,177 --> 00:28:16,439
And then they're going to have to spend time in the grassy happy land.

635
00:28:17,356 --> 00:28:18,197
So let's look at an example.

636
00:28:18,597 --> 00:28:20,540
For free-for-all politics, one thing you can do

637
00:28:20,600 --> 00:28:22,462
is limit players' agency over one another.

638
00:28:23,603 --> 00:28:24,745
So for example, in a foot race,

639
00:28:25,486 --> 00:28:26,647
it's very hard to play politics

640
00:28:26,747 --> 00:28:27,748
because you can't do anything

641
00:28:27,788 --> 00:28:29,671
to affect the other player's state for the most part.

642
00:28:31,146 --> 00:28:32,608
But there are software examples too.

643
00:28:33,228 --> 00:28:37,093
Battle royale games are actually kind of an incredible innovation in free-for-all games

644
00:28:37,634 --> 00:28:41,980
because players are so far apart and there's so much hidden information and there are so

645
00:28:42,060 --> 00:28:47,847
many players and lethality is so high that it's just not viable to play a political game.

646
00:28:47,927 --> 00:28:49,868
I can't be like, ah yeah, I know which player I'm going after.

647
00:28:49,888 --> 00:28:52,670
I mean, maybe you can, but it would be an insane idea.

648
00:28:53,210 --> 00:28:54,410
And you can't make alliances with people

649
00:28:54,450 --> 00:28:55,891
because they might just shoot you at any moment.

650
00:28:56,011 --> 00:28:57,472
You can try to do these things, but it's basically

651
00:28:57,512 --> 00:28:58,272
not a viable option.

652
00:28:58,352 --> 00:29:00,533
Instead, you're forced to play hard.

653
00:29:00,813 --> 00:29:02,895
You play the game of shooting and jumping around and

654
00:29:02,915 --> 00:29:03,255
bullying.

655
00:29:03,695 --> 00:29:04,976
That is what this game promised.

656
00:29:05,656 --> 00:29:07,957
It's limited your agency over other players, basically,

657
00:29:07,977 --> 00:29:08,998
through spreading you apart.

658
00:29:09,738 --> 00:29:11,479
And as a consequence, you don't get politics.

659
00:29:12,359 --> 00:29:15,020
So now the important part is, remember I said you always

660
00:29:15,040 --> 00:29:15,841
sacrifice something.

661
00:29:16,330 --> 00:29:18,550
even if it's a subtle implied goal.

662
00:29:19,210 --> 00:29:21,091
In this case, what you sacrifice is some of the

663
00:29:21,131 --> 00:29:22,731
PvP fantasy of control.

664
00:29:23,551 --> 00:29:25,952
A big part of PvP games, many of them, is being like,

665
00:29:26,072 --> 00:29:28,052
I own you, you are gonna do what I say,

666
00:29:28,072 --> 00:29:29,833
and I can take you down exactly the path

667
00:29:29,873 --> 00:29:30,553
I want to take you down.

668
00:29:31,153 --> 00:29:32,013
And this just isn't really,

669
00:29:32,033 --> 00:29:33,094
it's definitely not possible foot race,

670
00:29:33,134 --> 00:29:36,274
and it's sort of not possible for most of a battle royale game.

671
00:29:36,595 --> 00:29:38,035
You've limited agency over each other,

672
00:29:38,055 --> 00:29:41,156
and so naturally players cannot impact each other as much.

673
00:29:42,316 --> 00:29:42,456
Okay.

674
00:29:43,840 --> 00:29:45,662
So now let's see a second example, which I call gates.

675
00:29:46,162 --> 00:29:48,965
Gates are basically a softer touch version of barriers.

676
00:29:49,325 --> 00:29:51,627
You don't completely lock the player out of the actions that

677
00:29:51,647 --> 00:29:54,810
might allow the promises to break, but you do make them

678
00:29:54,830 --> 00:29:55,930
very difficult to perform.

679
00:29:56,431 --> 00:29:59,113
And challenge is something we get to add in wherever we see

680
00:29:59,153 --> 00:29:59,834
appropriating games.

681
00:29:59,874 --> 00:30:01,735
It's a nice, specific affordance of the medium.

682
00:30:02,776 --> 00:30:05,959
So for example, you might spend most of your time not

683
00:30:06,219 --> 00:30:07,941
in political play, but players might figure out a way to do

684
00:30:07,961 --> 00:30:08,381
it a little bit.

685
00:30:09,895 --> 00:30:13,838
So in the case of Free-for-All Politics, one thing we can do is limit visibility of players'

686
00:30:13,858 --> 00:30:14,219
success.

687
00:30:15,720 --> 00:30:20,563
So in PlayStation All-Stars Battle Royale, which I was a technical designer on, it's

688
00:30:20,603 --> 00:30:22,605
another brawler for a player brawler.

689
00:30:22,625 --> 00:30:25,827
One of the things we did was we hid the player's scores.

690
00:30:26,207 --> 00:30:29,310
Notice there's no score in here listed, and not only did we hide it, we actually made

691
00:30:29,330 --> 00:30:30,791
it harder for players to reason about.

692
00:30:31,211 --> 00:30:33,713
Your score in this game is twice your kills minus your deaths.

693
00:30:34,468 --> 00:30:37,871
So that means that it's kind of hard to play this game,

694
00:30:37,891 --> 00:30:39,893
play as hard as you can, and also keep track of everybody's score

695
00:30:39,933 --> 00:30:40,733
and know who's in the lead.

696
00:30:41,274 --> 00:30:43,515
And moreover, you sort of have this plausible deniability

697
00:30:43,535 --> 00:30:44,796
that lets you just go hard.

698
00:30:44,816 --> 00:30:46,798
Because you're like, nobody knows how well I'm doing.

699
00:30:46,858 --> 00:30:49,020
Like, I'll just go ahead and just kick as much ass as I want.

700
00:30:49,060 --> 00:30:52,903
And that's what lets players play freely and not go as hard into politics.

701
00:30:54,918 --> 00:30:55,559
So what do we give up?

702
00:30:56,339 --> 00:31:00,363
Well, among other things, we give up some of the tension of buzzer beaters.

703
00:31:00,403 --> 00:31:03,546
We don't get these situations where we know all the players are really, really close together

704
00:31:03,566 --> 00:31:04,327
and you wonder who's going to win.

705
00:31:04,347 --> 00:31:06,489
Because you kind of just don't know.

706
00:31:06,509 --> 00:31:09,972
And then the game ends, and you're like, oh, turns out Jerry won.

707
00:31:10,112 --> 00:31:10,292
OK.

708
00:31:12,354 --> 00:31:14,676
So the third example is carrots.

709
00:31:15,664 --> 00:31:17,666
This is where, you know, we change the objective.

710
00:31:17,686 --> 00:31:20,448
If the objective is what's drawing them through these problematic states,

711
00:31:21,269 --> 00:31:23,210
let's change it or let's create some new goals

712
00:31:23,290 --> 00:31:25,672
that help keep them following these objectives

713
00:31:26,133 --> 00:31:28,174
all the way to the goal

714
00:31:28,434 --> 00:31:29,996
without spending time doing political play.

715
00:31:31,937 --> 00:31:33,659
So, how can we do this with free-for-all games?

716
00:31:34,159 --> 00:31:35,820
One way is to add metagame effects.

717
00:31:36,541 --> 00:31:38,783
This is kind of not a well-known technique, I think,

718
00:31:38,843 --> 00:31:41,665
but, you know, I found my way here through using this framework

719
00:31:41,685 --> 00:31:42,966
and I looked for examples of games that did it.

720
00:31:43,997 --> 00:31:48,816
So an interesting case, it's actually in a tournament context, for settlers of Catan tournaments.

721
00:31:49,532 --> 00:31:52,713
They don't use, you know, whether or not you won a game

722
00:31:52,954 --> 00:31:54,314
to determine your placement in the tournament

723
00:31:54,534 --> 00:31:55,315
and how you move through it.

724
00:31:55,735 --> 00:31:58,337
They actually use your performance in an individual game.

725
00:31:58,757 --> 00:32:00,438
So if you win a game, you get four points.

726
00:32:01,038 --> 00:32:03,099
But if you get third place, you get two points.

727
00:32:03,520 --> 00:32:05,160
And all of these points end up determining

728
00:32:05,241 --> 00:32:06,521
how you move through the tournament

729
00:32:06,861 --> 00:32:07,722
and how well you perform.

730
00:32:08,262 --> 00:32:09,763
So this weird thing happens

731
00:32:09,783 --> 00:32:11,584
where I'm not so incentivized to play politics

732
00:32:11,604 --> 00:32:13,705
because I don't care as much who wins or who loses.

733
00:32:14,026 --> 00:32:16,287
What I really care about is raising my own performance up.

734
00:32:16,507 --> 00:32:18,828
Just getting from third place to second place is, like, great for me.

735
00:32:19,764 --> 00:32:22,606
And I think politics is naturally diminished as a consequence.

736
00:32:23,887 --> 00:32:25,228
But there's also the side effect,

737
00:32:25,668 --> 00:32:29,090
which is you kind of diminish the magic circle of an individual game.

738
00:32:30,091 --> 00:32:33,753
Right? Like, the game doesn't have this win or lose clarity.

739
00:32:33,793 --> 00:32:36,535
It's just kind of like, oh, OK, more points for the point bucket

740
00:32:36,835 --> 00:32:38,996
that's going to end up determining maybe what I really care about,

741
00:32:39,056 --> 00:32:40,177
which is whether I win the tournament.

742
00:32:41,518 --> 00:32:41,718
All right.

743
00:32:42,381 --> 00:32:46,823
So the fourth technique, again I'm going to say these are pretty much all you can do to deal with curse problems,

744
00:32:48,243 --> 00:32:48,784
is s'mores.

745
00:32:49,244 --> 00:32:53,325
Which is to say, okay, players are violating the promises that we think we're making for them,

746
00:32:54,086 --> 00:32:56,827
but maybe we can just make that fun. Maybe we can lean into that so much

747
00:32:57,307 --> 00:33:01,348
that the promise kind of dissipates and players understand that they're playing a different game.

748
00:33:01,368 --> 00:33:06,991
So you basically give them marshmallows to melt in the fire and then you got s'mores. Yeah, okay.

749
00:33:08,171 --> 00:33:10,532
So, you know, players will spend their time here and it's still great.

750
00:33:11,797 --> 00:33:15,278
So, how do you do that with free-for-all games?

751
00:33:15,978 --> 00:33:17,719
Well, you've probably seen games like this before.

752
00:33:17,739 --> 00:33:20,059
You can give players tools to actually lean

753
00:33:20,100 --> 00:33:22,460
into that political play, make it really deep and fun,

754
00:33:23,020 --> 00:33:24,641
through, for example, adding secrecy,

755
00:33:24,681 --> 00:33:27,101
which is sorely missing from brawlers.

756
00:33:28,902 --> 00:33:31,763
Especially if you don't mind your players

757
00:33:31,803 --> 00:33:33,643
never being friends again, you can give them diplomacy.

758
00:33:34,869 --> 00:33:37,091
And they'll have a great time for one game.

759
00:33:38,932 --> 00:33:39,992
And you know, what happens here is like,

760
00:33:40,012 --> 00:33:42,774
they have this incredible game of Game of Thrones-esque intrigue.

761
00:33:43,014 --> 00:33:44,315
And you can see it right there on the box.

762
00:33:44,375 --> 00:33:47,177
It says, The Game of International Intrigue.

763
00:33:47,417 --> 00:33:48,297
It's very intriguing.

764
00:33:48,698 --> 00:33:51,059
But the consequence is that you have this

765
00:33:51,640 --> 00:33:53,841
lack of emphasis on moment-to-moment action.

766
00:33:54,161 --> 00:33:56,162
Right? It's not so much about exactly where I place my units.

767
00:33:56,202 --> 00:33:59,084
It's really about the relationships I break along the way.

768
00:33:59,104 --> 00:33:59,144
So.

769
00:34:02,436 --> 00:34:05,677
And I also want to call out, by the way, that first example that I showed you of creating

770
00:34:05,717 --> 00:34:07,158
smash through weakening promises.

771
00:34:07,978 --> 00:34:10,379
This is another example of s'mores.

772
00:34:10,439 --> 00:34:13,401
We've said, okay, we had these hard promises that this game seemed to imply.

773
00:34:13,481 --> 00:34:17,262
What can we do to change our game so the game itself no longer makes those promises to the

774
00:34:17,302 --> 00:34:17,522
player?

775
00:34:18,363 --> 00:34:20,124
So another instantiation of s'mores.

776
00:34:21,724 --> 00:34:21,944
Okay.

777
00:34:22,545 --> 00:34:24,365
So you've seen the four techniques.

778
00:34:24,665 --> 00:34:26,746
Barriers, gates, carrots, and s'mores.

779
00:34:27,829 --> 00:34:31,673
I want to call out that these are, they are general purpose design techniques.

780
00:34:31,953 --> 00:34:34,996
It's not like you can't use these for uncursed problems.

781
00:34:35,537 --> 00:34:37,959
The thing that I think is interesting is that this is sort of all you can do

782
00:34:38,580 --> 00:34:39,460
in a cursed problem setting.

783
00:34:41,015 --> 00:34:43,955
I really want you to think of this as a tiny design framework.

784
00:34:44,176 --> 00:34:47,216
Something to apply when you get into certain kinds of situations.

785
00:34:47,896 --> 00:34:49,737
It's not going to tell you how to do the work.

786
00:34:50,157 --> 00:34:51,877
You're not going to be like, oh god, what do I do?

787
00:34:51,977 --> 00:34:53,658
Oh, I know carrots, now I know how to solve this problem.

788
00:34:54,398 --> 00:34:56,718
But it gives you a structure for a difficult creative process.

789
00:34:56,758 --> 00:34:58,098
This has worked for me many times.

790
00:34:58,118 --> 00:35:01,459
I'm looking at a problem and I actually think through these four categories.

791
00:35:01,539 --> 00:35:03,760
It prompts my brain to think about directions.

792
00:35:04,300 --> 00:35:05,980
that I never would have gone down otherwise.

793
00:35:06,320 --> 00:35:08,321
Because your brain doesn't want to make these sacrifices, right?

794
00:35:08,341 --> 00:35:10,742
It wants to solve the problem exactly as defined, and it can't.

795
00:35:11,302 --> 00:35:12,443
So you need something to tell you, like,

796
00:35:12,483 --> 00:35:13,963
hey, have you, you know, considered, like,

797
00:35:14,003 --> 00:35:15,184
refinancing your home or something?

798
00:35:16,344 --> 00:35:17,965
So, um, that's it.

799
00:35:18,545 --> 00:35:20,626
Now I'm just gonna give you a few more examples.

800
00:35:20,646 --> 00:35:21,426
That's all we're doing right now.

801
00:35:21,446 --> 00:35:23,627
We're just doing examples so you can build intuition

802
00:35:24,167 --> 00:35:25,668
for how these techniques work.

803
00:35:26,348 --> 00:35:28,369
And I'm gonna show you exactly one more example

804
00:35:28,389 --> 00:35:29,069
for each of the techniques.

805
00:35:30,050 --> 00:35:31,930
I already showed you all four techniques

806
00:35:32,290 --> 00:35:33,191
on free-for-all politics.

807
00:35:33,997 --> 00:35:37,561
But now I'm going to do two for another problem and two for one after that, just in the interest of time.

808
00:35:37,681 --> 00:35:39,984
You can apply all of these techniques to all of these problems.

809
00:35:40,765 --> 00:35:42,468
So I'll talk about the co-op abuse problem.

810
00:35:44,110 --> 00:35:45,031
This sucks.

811
00:35:46,925 --> 00:35:53,127
So high stakes co-op games often involve a lot of terrible treatment between players.

812
00:35:53,827 --> 00:35:57,789
And I think, you know, as game developers we have a responsibility to do what we can to make this better.

813
00:35:58,589 --> 00:36:07,512
And some of this, as Meg Giantso eloquently said yesterday, involves, you know, telling the worst players, like the Nazis, to get the fuck out of our games.

814
00:36:08,152 --> 00:36:11,093
But there also is, I think, we have a responsibility as designers as well.

815
00:36:11,894 --> 00:36:13,794
to say like what can we do in our games

816
00:36:14,315 --> 00:36:16,596
to make this behavior less likely.

817
00:36:17,336 --> 00:36:19,937
Now unfortunately, it feels like there's this fundamental incompatibility.

818
00:36:21,358 --> 00:36:23,039
Players want to play to win, right?

819
00:36:23,079 --> 00:36:25,600
These games signal themselves as sort of win-oriented.

820
00:36:26,440 --> 00:36:28,922
But a lot of players also, they come for social belonging.

821
00:36:29,622 --> 00:36:31,983
The reason why you're playing a co-op game, among others,

822
00:36:32,043 --> 00:36:33,744
is because you want to feel like a part of something.

823
00:36:34,678 --> 00:36:36,459
These two things, they often don't go well together

824
00:36:36,499 --> 00:36:38,900
because players who want to play to win will not be satisfied.

825
00:36:39,460 --> 00:36:42,761
Human beings feel like a game is fair when they win 70% of the time.

826
00:36:42,781 --> 00:36:44,982
And that's probably not going to happen in your PvP game.

827
00:36:45,483 --> 00:36:48,884
So if that player also is lacking anger management skills

828
00:36:48,944 --> 00:36:51,265
and tends to blame others more than themselves...

829
00:36:52,297 --> 00:36:54,577
You're gonna get them feeling dissatisfied and frustrated.

830
00:36:54,597 --> 00:36:58,059
The social belonging needing player wants psychological safety,

831
00:36:58,339 --> 00:36:59,719
needs it for that to happen,

832
00:37:00,340 --> 00:37:01,660
but these things don't go together.

833
00:37:01,680 --> 00:37:03,721
And I say sometimes here because it depends on the player,

834
00:37:03,801 --> 00:37:05,061
depends on the player's state of mind.

835
00:37:05,641 --> 00:37:07,262
It feels like there's this fundamental tension

836
00:37:07,402 --> 00:37:09,363
in any co-op game that has high stakes,

837
00:37:09,683 --> 00:37:10,683
PVP or otherwise.

838
00:37:12,124 --> 00:37:14,045
But of course, so the problem is curse,

839
00:37:14,065 --> 00:37:15,625
but of course as I said there are things you can do.

840
00:37:15,765 --> 00:37:17,586
You just need to be willing to give something up

841
00:37:17,826 --> 00:37:19,326
if you really, really want to go down this path.

842
00:37:21,822 --> 00:37:23,964
By the way, it was funny, totally independently,

843
00:37:24,024 --> 00:37:25,665
a couple of my colleagues at Riot,

844
00:37:26,886 --> 00:37:28,027
Naomi MacArthur and Kenny Shores,

845
00:37:28,047 --> 00:37:29,869
gave a talk yesterday or the day before,

846
00:37:30,089 --> 00:37:31,430
Impact of Social Systems in Game Design

847
00:37:31,470 --> 00:37:32,251
and Player Interactions.

848
00:37:32,691 --> 00:37:33,852
She talked about a similar topic,

849
00:37:34,213 --> 00:37:37,876
what you can do in your design to de-emphasize player abuse.

850
00:37:38,216 --> 00:37:39,057
That's a cool one to check out.

851
00:37:40,818 --> 00:37:45,702
So, we're gonna look at barriers now.

852
00:37:46,983 --> 00:37:47,404
All right, so.

853
00:37:48,526 --> 00:37:50,588
One approach is to just limit player communication.

854
00:37:51,129 --> 00:37:51,289
Right?

855
00:37:52,090 --> 00:37:52,190
Uh...

856
00:37:53,091 --> 00:37:55,033
And you can see a great example of that in a game like Journey.

857
00:37:55,353 --> 00:37:57,475
It's not a high-stakes co-op game, but we can still learn from it.

858
00:37:58,376 --> 00:37:58,997
They basically said,

859
00:37:59,017 --> 00:38:01,899
hey, we want to create an online game in which everyone can have a beautiful time together

860
00:38:01,919 --> 00:38:03,381
and they cannot treat each other like shit.

861
00:38:03,941 --> 00:38:04,362
And they did it.

862
00:38:04,402 --> 00:38:07,545
They made this game where basically you can run around and walk and jump and make beautiful pings.

863
00:38:08,086 --> 00:38:09,447
And you feel connected to someone.

864
00:38:09,567 --> 00:38:11,049
And it's a huge success.

865
00:38:11,916 --> 00:38:15,019
And you can generalize this to PvP games, even though we

866
00:38:15,039 --> 00:38:15,680
haven't seen much of it.

867
00:38:15,700 --> 00:38:18,483
I think Apex Legends is proof that you can, because they

868
00:38:18,523 --> 00:38:22,428
have such a kind of communicative ping system that

869
00:38:22,448 --> 00:38:25,251
you could easily imagine just turning off voice and text

870
00:38:25,271 --> 00:38:27,193
communication in this game entirely and still

871
00:38:27,233 --> 00:38:27,994
having a great game.

872
00:38:28,815 --> 00:38:31,898
The sacrifice here, among others, is the rich social

873
00:38:31,918 --> 00:38:33,100
channel for relationship building.

874
00:38:34,061 --> 00:38:36,463
Like, we play co-op games.

875
00:38:36,623 --> 00:38:39,706
One of the reasons is so that we can build relationships,

876
00:38:39,766 --> 00:38:40,207
make friends.

877
00:38:40,227 --> 00:38:42,189
And it's very hard to practice disclosure when you

878
00:38:42,209 --> 00:38:43,229
can't use your words.

879
00:38:43,850 --> 00:38:46,833
So maybe there's some way to tie this together into a game

880
00:38:46,853 --> 00:38:48,434
that slowly opens up into more communication.

881
00:38:48,494 --> 00:38:50,896
But you see that we are giving something up by doing this.

882
00:38:52,677 --> 00:38:54,438
Alright, so technique two is gates.

883
00:38:55,118 --> 00:38:57,419
Can we make it difficult to abuse each other?

884
00:38:57,939 --> 00:38:59,240
And yeah, I mean, one way to do this

885
00:38:59,300 --> 00:39:00,941
is to limit individual responsibility.

886
00:39:02,122 --> 00:39:03,822
And Heroes of the Storm, I think,

887
00:39:03,862 --> 00:39:04,923
does this very intentionally.

888
00:39:05,203 --> 00:39:06,844
They take the MOBA formula and they say,

889
00:39:07,264 --> 00:39:09,105
let's have players share responsibility more.

890
00:39:09,145 --> 00:39:10,646
Let's make it so everybody contributes

891
00:39:10,666 --> 00:39:12,947
to a shared gold pool, for example.

892
00:39:13,407 --> 00:39:17,550
And as a consequence, I don't even know who is doing well and who is doing poorly, at least on this front.

893
00:39:17,930 --> 00:39:22,593
And it makes it that much harder for me to pick someone out to abuse, to blame my problems on.

894
00:39:23,574 --> 00:39:26,616
There's an even more extreme example of this in something like, a game like Werewolf or Mafia,

895
00:39:27,056 --> 00:39:32,840
or any social deduction game in which, you know, one of the teams doesn't know who else is on their team.

896
00:39:33,260 --> 00:39:35,982
It's really hard for me to flame at you for not helping me out,

897
00:39:36,002 --> 00:39:37,923
if I don't even know that you're supposed to be helping me out.

898
00:39:38,610 --> 00:39:41,132
At the end of the game, players may all hate each other, but at least during the game,

899
00:39:41,712 --> 00:39:42,272
it's all kosher.

900
00:39:42,953 --> 00:39:46,655
So here we give up some of the fantasy of harmonious cooperation, right?

901
00:39:47,155 --> 00:39:52,038
Like because players are less individualized, there is less of that Ocean's Eleven feeling

902
00:39:52,058 --> 00:39:55,880
of like, you know, I'm using my bomb skills and you're using your not werewolf skills

903
00:39:55,900 --> 00:39:59,623
or whatever they are, and each of us is coming together to contribute individually to this

904
00:39:59,963 --> 00:40:00,823
fantasy of cooperation.

905
00:40:02,407 --> 00:40:04,710
Okay, so we saw barriers and gates for co-op abuse.

906
00:40:05,351 --> 00:40:08,195
Now, we are going to see carrots and s'mores

907
00:40:08,315 --> 00:40:10,278
for what I call the quantified creativity problem.

908
00:40:11,880 --> 00:40:12,821
So this is The Sims 4.

909
00:40:12,941 --> 00:40:15,044
It's an example of a creative game with goals.

910
00:40:16,903 --> 00:40:20,947
Now, I had this experience when I bought The Sims when I was a teenager that might resonate

911
00:40:20,967 --> 00:40:23,709
with you, which is I was super excited by it initially.

912
00:40:23,849 --> 00:40:27,393
I loved the, you know, the weird storytelling and the relationships and building crazy houses

913
00:40:27,853 --> 00:40:28,374
and so on.

914
00:40:29,154 --> 00:40:34,399
But slowly I got sucked into what almost felt like another game, which was the rat race

915
00:40:34,740 --> 00:40:36,221
of improving my Sims career.

916
00:40:36,682 --> 00:40:38,724
And he was a scientist and I really, really wanted to get him to level 10.

917
00:40:38,764 --> 00:40:40,946
Because when he got to level 10, he was an astronaut.

918
00:40:41,246 --> 00:40:44,189
And I was so excited and finally I got there and I spent all this time and all this effort

919
00:40:44,209 --> 00:40:47,472
just focusing on leveling him up and, you know, living the life I needed to to get him

920
00:40:47,512 --> 00:40:47,673
there.

921
00:40:48,013 --> 00:40:50,075
And he goes into space and I'm like, yes.

922
00:40:50,435 --> 00:40:53,258
And he comes down and like I think both of us got post-space depression.

923
00:40:55,540 --> 00:40:57,082
because it was like, what's left to do now?

924
00:40:57,122 --> 00:40:57,882
We got there, right?

925
00:40:57,942 --> 00:40:59,023
Like, my life dream is complete.

926
00:40:59,524 --> 00:41:01,765
And I noticed I completely forgot about what initially

927
00:41:01,805 --> 00:41:05,168
interested me about the game, which was this creative play,

928
00:41:05,188 --> 00:41:08,010
this wild storytelling and fun and expressiveness.

929
00:41:08,851 --> 00:41:12,794
And this is the problem, is players see a game like this.

930
00:41:13,014 --> 00:41:14,235
They want to express themselves.

931
00:41:14,255 --> 00:41:15,557
The game clearly signals they should.

932
00:41:16,117 --> 00:41:18,159
But the game also wants to draw them in with goals.

933
00:41:18,699 --> 00:41:20,461
And that ends up making players want to progress their

934
00:41:20,481 --> 00:41:22,923
character or whatever form the progression takes.

935
00:41:23,829 --> 00:41:28,951
And these things are in conflict because expressing yourself involves following intrinsic goals,

936
00:41:29,011 --> 00:41:30,852
kind of like following your heart, basically.

937
00:41:31,792 --> 00:41:36,274
And progressing your character involves following extrinsic goals, doing what the game says

938
00:41:36,294 --> 00:41:36,694
you should do.

939
00:41:36,834 --> 00:41:38,075
And it's pretty well known that...

940
00:41:39,075 --> 00:41:42,297
Extrinsic goals tend to subsume intrinsic goals, right?

941
00:41:42,437 --> 00:41:44,758
The more time I spend focusing on getting those carrots,

942
00:41:44,858 --> 00:41:46,899
the less I really care about what I came for in the first place.

943
00:41:46,959 --> 00:41:47,539
It's just kind of...

944
00:41:47,939 --> 00:41:49,620
Seems to be a rule of thumb in games and in life.

945
00:41:50,180 --> 00:41:51,320
So these two things don't go together.

946
00:41:51,841 --> 00:41:52,641
The problem is cursed.

947
00:41:53,321 --> 00:41:57,203
And note that The Sims is obviously a wildly successful game, as I said,

948
00:41:57,563 --> 00:42:00,824
but I suspect that the players who really latch onto this game

949
00:42:01,064 --> 00:42:03,165
are the ones who completely ignore the progression, right?

950
00:42:03,185 --> 00:42:04,386
For whom it basically does nothing,

951
00:42:04,746 --> 00:42:06,506
and who just really focus on that self-expression.

952
00:42:07,511 --> 00:42:10,876
And I think the designers clearly here want to create a game in which both of these things

953
00:42:10,916 --> 00:42:13,159
can come together, right, into this harmonious union.

954
00:42:14,020 --> 00:42:15,983
So can we do this with these techniques?

955
00:42:17,025 --> 00:42:17,726
Let's try carrots.

956
00:42:19,708 --> 00:42:21,351
So can we incentivize players to be creative?

957
00:42:22,904 --> 00:42:25,266
Well, yeah, we can actually give them concrete reasons to be creative.

958
00:42:25,306 --> 00:42:28,528
And this is super weird, because this is going to turn your game into a very different game.

959
00:42:28,848 --> 00:42:30,830
But it might still share some of the DNA.

960
00:42:31,190 --> 00:42:33,752
Like one game that kind of does this is Clash of Clans.

961
00:42:34,152 --> 00:42:37,214
It's a game about building all these towns, putting all your little stuff down, and you

962
00:42:37,254 --> 00:42:40,076
can make really wild and creative shapes and layouts.

963
00:42:40,497 --> 00:42:41,838
And you actually are incentivized to.

964
00:42:42,378 --> 00:42:43,698
because you want to play off meta.

965
00:42:43,878 --> 00:42:46,739
If players are going to come at you with a specific, you know, set of armies

966
00:42:46,780 --> 00:42:49,040
that are there to destroy whatever the typical maps are,

967
00:42:49,200 --> 00:42:53,062
you benefit from doing this weird creative map, this weird layout, right?

968
00:42:53,082 --> 00:42:53,702
You're going to tend to win.

969
00:42:53,722 --> 00:42:56,243
It's like bringing a magic deck to a tournament that no one was prepared for.

970
00:42:57,564 --> 00:42:59,504
So, that's cool. Like, you still get to be creative,

971
00:42:59,924 --> 00:43:02,045
but the game is actually telling you to, at least to some extent.

972
00:43:03,077 --> 00:43:06,381
For a very different example, you can look at AlphaBear, which we made at SpryFox.

973
00:43:07,543 --> 00:43:11,107
And this is a game, it's a word game, you spell words from tiles on a grid,

974
00:43:11,668 --> 00:43:14,871
and the tiles expire, and you want to use up all the letters before they expire.

975
00:43:15,973 --> 00:43:17,495
And there's this weird tension where players,

976
00:43:17,995 --> 00:43:20,398
they try to win this game by spelling, using all the words,

977
00:43:21,119 --> 00:43:22,020
but they also...

978
00:43:22,972 --> 00:43:25,774
really like spelling funny, weird words.

979
00:43:26,015 --> 00:43:28,457
Like, that's a kind of creative self-expression to get through the game.

980
00:43:28,737 --> 00:43:30,759
And the game was not incentivizing at all.

981
00:43:31,139 --> 00:43:32,841
There was nothing pushing players towards

982
00:43:33,241 --> 00:43:34,523
this kind of fun, creative play.

983
00:43:35,403 --> 00:43:37,165
And then, for totally unrelated reasons,

984
00:43:37,645 --> 00:43:40,548
we added this Mad Libs feature that would take

985
00:43:41,229 --> 00:43:44,552
words that you spelled in the game and then put them automatically into a Mad Lib.

986
00:43:44,872 --> 00:43:45,913
So you spelled YETI and it says,

987
00:43:45,993 --> 00:43:48,596
I code so that someday we can afford a YETI of our own.

988
00:43:49,459 --> 00:43:53,463
And maybe if you're really lucky, you can afford a whole town of yetis.

989
00:43:54,464 --> 00:43:55,345
That's some industry humor.

990
00:43:57,006 --> 00:43:57,327
Look it up.

991
00:43:57,467 --> 00:43:58,087
It's a bad story.

992
00:43:58,668 --> 00:43:59,448
Okay.

993
00:44:01,390 --> 00:44:04,453
So the thing about what's happening here is players actually got really incentivized.

994
00:44:05,059 --> 00:44:08,720
to make these funny, weird words, right?

995
00:44:08,740 --> 00:44:10,201
To spell them out, even though it has nothing to do

996
00:44:10,221 --> 00:44:11,301
with the incentives of the actual game.

997
00:44:11,601 --> 00:44:14,863
We've created this sort of social, intrinsic meta-game

998
00:44:15,383 --> 00:44:18,464
around the kind of extrinsically motivated internal game.

999
00:44:18,484 --> 00:44:20,504
And even though there's no real scoring or anything

1000
00:44:20,524 --> 00:44:21,345
in this social game, you know,

1001
00:44:21,365 --> 00:44:22,565
there are likes on Twitter or whatever,

1002
00:44:22,605 --> 00:44:23,506
people would share these a lot,

1003
00:44:23,806 --> 00:44:25,206
and it felt like the players could play

1004
00:44:25,246 --> 00:44:26,927
these two games simultaneously in harmony.

1005
00:44:27,227 --> 00:44:28,267
And it almost seemed like the fact

1006
00:44:28,307 --> 00:44:29,768
that they were separate games made it easier

1007
00:44:30,088 --> 00:44:31,388
to hold both of these things in their head.

1008
00:44:32,048 --> 00:44:35,390
Players really enjoyed looking forward to spelling the words that would make these math labs.

1009
00:44:37,130 --> 00:44:41,152
Okay, what do you sacrifice? You sacrifice the safety of unconstrained creativity.

1010
00:44:41,912 --> 00:44:45,093
Obviously in both of these examples, I don't get to just go wild and do anything I want, right?

1011
00:44:45,113 --> 00:44:50,896
I'm really, I still am trying to win, you know, and that means I'm going to be way less expressive than I would be otherwise.

1012
00:44:52,196 --> 00:44:55,617
But maybe that's okay for you as a designer. In each of these cases, you're developing your game,

1013
00:44:55,637 --> 00:44:57,878
you have to decide what kinds of sacrifices you're willing to make.

1014
00:44:59,033 --> 00:45:01,474
Alright, for a final example, how do we use s'mores?

1015
00:45:01,494 --> 00:45:04,496
How do we say, okay, maybe the lack of creativity isn't so bad.

1016
00:45:05,957 --> 00:45:09,099
Well, you'll end up in a very different place here,

1017
00:45:09,600 --> 00:45:10,960
but I claim there's still a connection.

1018
00:45:11,901 --> 00:45:14,363
You can create rich, deep goals around the simulation

1019
00:45:14,403 --> 00:45:16,664
in a game like SimCity or The Sims,

1020
00:45:17,605 --> 00:45:19,706
and maybe get a totally different game.

1021
00:45:19,726 --> 00:45:21,027
What you actually get here is Civ.

1022
00:45:21,928 --> 00:45:26,731
Civilization in a weird way is SimCity with the creativity kind of sucked out.

1023
00:45:26,751 --> 00:45:30,694
It's not that you can't be creative in Civilization, it's that you wouldn't be.

1024
00:45:30,734 --> 00:45:33,897
This isn't the game you would pick because they realize that there's so much depth there

1025
00:45:33,977 --> 00:45:38,240
in the core gameplay, there's so much strategy and so many interesting constraints and goals,

1026
00:45:38,540 --> 00:45:39,961
that they just lean right into it and say,

1027
00:45:39,981 --> 00:45:40,942
okay, we're going to make a different game.

1028
00:45:40,962 --> 00:45:44,284
But it still has some of that core DNA of what, say, SimCity is.

1029
00:45:44,945 --> 00:45:48,147
And, you know, you focus a lot more on winning these games

1030
00:45:48,167 --> 00:45:50,269
than you do on, like, making a really weird Civilization.

1031
00:45:51,250 --> 00:45:55,134
And of course, here you've given up most of the original self-expression goal, right?

1032
00:45:55,154 --> 00:45:57,075
This is kind of the most extreme of the sacrifices.

1033
00:45:57,416 --> 00:45:59,137
But you want to know the full spectrum,

1034
00:45:59,497 --> 00:46:03,321
because you might find yourself in a really cool space by being willing to relax your goal.

1035
00:46:04,742 --> 00:46:05,983
So, that's it.

1036
00:46:06,243 --> 00:46:07,844
These examples I've shown, two examples for each.

1037
00:46:08,265 --> 00:46:10,687
There are a lot more out there, but it's as much as I have time to show you,

1038
00:46:10,707 --> 00:46:12,969
so you can build this intuition for how to use these techniques.

1039
00:46:14,350 --> 00:46:14,770
So to wrap up.

1040
00:46:16,442 --> 00:46:18,163
Curse problems cannot just be solved.

1041
00:46:18,483 --> 00:46:19,523
They require a sacrifice.

1042
00:46:20,204 --> 00:46:21,024
You have to give something up.

1043
00:46:22,245 --> 00:46:24,787
But, there's kind of an exciting silver lining

1044
00:46:25,047 --> 00:46:26,828
to the existence of these curse problems.

1045
00:46:27,528 --> 00:46:29,610
I've talked about what to do when you run into one, right,

1046
00:46:29,630 --> 00:46:31,130
and you kind of stare it face down.

1047
00:46:32,972 --> 00:46:34,112
But you can also seek them out.

1048
00:46:35,133 --> 00:46:36,694
Curse problems are the highest hanging fruit out there.

1049
00:46:36,734 --> 00:46:37,514
Like, people are ignoring them

1050
00:46:37,534 --> 00:46:38,915
because a lot of people think they're impossible.

1051
00:46:39,729 --> 00:46:43,491
But they're also the ripest problems.

1052
00:46:43,831 --> 00:46:46,492
They have so much potential for finding new ways

1053
00:46:46,512 --> 00:46:47,252
to create games.

1054
00:46:48,052 --> 00:46:51,014
And if you actually seek them out and decide to pivot a

1055
00:46:51,034 --> 00:46:53,154
little bit, you find this whole new open area.

1056
00:46:53,215 --> 00:46:54,515
So here are some challenges.

1057
00:46:55,836 --> 00:46:57,916
Just a few things that people have told me are impossible.

1058
00:46:58,157 --> 00:46:59,197
There are many more cool ones.

1059
00:47:00,097 --> 00:47:03,219
So one is making a multiplayer game with player-generated

1060
00:47:03,259 --> 00:47:06,960
content that somehow lives in harmonious balance, that isn't

1061
00:47:06,980 --> 00:47:07,460
totally broken.

1062
00:47:08,842 --> 00:47:11,224
Another is creating PvP games, like I said,

1063
00:47:11,284 --> 00:47:13,546
in which all players feel there was a just outcome,

1064
00:47:14,087 --> 00:47:16,128
despite the fact that they want to win 70% of the time.

1065
00:47:17,009 --> 00:47:18,770
And the last one is a game that maintains

1066
00:47:18,790 --> 00:47:20,292
a sense of mystery and discovery

1067
00:47:20,772 --> 00:47:21,553
in the age of the internet

1068
00:47:21,573 --> 00:47:22,914
in which all secrets are laid bare.

1069
00:47:23,434 --> 00:47:25,196
These sort of seem fundamentally contradictory,

1070
00:47:25,556 --> 00:47:26,857
but the idea is when you have a contradiction,

1071
00:47:26,877 --> 00:47:29,519
you only have to pull out kind of one pin of those promises

1072
00:47:29,599 --> 00:47:30,920
and you get this whole wide open space.

1073
00:47:32,321 --> 00:47:36,024
So, the next time you find yourself wandering the desert,

1074
00:47:37,037 --> 00:47:40,038
This cursed to search forever for the solution to your problem.

1075
00:47:40,778 --> 00:47:41,879
And maybe with your whole team with you.

1076
00:47:43,059 --> 00:47:43,479
Stop looking.

1077
00:47:44,340 --> 00:47:44,780
Turn around.

1078
00:47:45,720 --> 00:47:47,521
There is a lush forest of possibility behind you.

1079
00:47:48,801 --> 00:47:49,041
Thanks.

